liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Indigenous Australians Minister Linda Burney says she is "emotional" as the Voice to Parliament legislation is set to pass parliament. The Senate will hold vote today to finalise the form of the referendum and the proposed constitutional change. Once passed, the six-month time limit on when the referendum can be held will also start. The government has flagged the referendum to establish an Indigenous Voice will be held between October and December. Burney describes the day of the vote as "momentous". "I'm feeling quite emotional actually," she tells ABC Radio. "Then we will see the campaigns get into full swing." Nationals Leader David Littleproud says he does not support wording for the 'no' case in the referendum pamphlet that included language such as "racialise" or describing the voice as a "smokescreen". "I'm not prepared to put my weight behind those sort of words," he tells ABC Radio. "I don't think that would advance a mature discussion, create the respectful environment for Australians to make a personal decision about this, and I intend to use my influence in that."
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Senate to vote on final form of Indigenous Voice referendum today

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Federal Treasurer Jim Chalmers says the national economy is prepared to take on global headwinds, following data showing Australia outperforming international peers. Australia had higher employment growth during the Albanese government's first year in office than other major economies, according to new data from the Treasury Department. Between May 2022 and May 2023, 465,000 jobs were created, the highest number for any new government on record. In the year since May 2022, Australia recorded 3.4 percent employment growth. That compares with: 2.7 per cent in the US 1.8 per cent in Canada 1.5 per cent in Italy 0.8 per cent in Germany 0.3 per cent in Japan Chalmers says while the economy faces challenges, the country is in a strong position. "This is a remarkable achievement for the economy and for the Australian people," he says.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Treasurer Jim Chalmers trumpets employment growth numbers

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The ABC's senior business correspondent Peter Ryan on AM this morning discussed the Treasurer Jim Chalmers's view that the strong jobs market is highlighting the economy's resilience to interest rate hikes and inflation pressures. The problem is that the Reserve Bank is likely to keep hiking interest rates until the economy is a little less resilient. RBA forecasts generally show the unemployment rate will need to reach around 4.5% before inflation will be back within its target range of 2-3 per cent. Last week's surprisingly strong jobs numbers, with 75,900 positions added in and May and unemployment falling back from 3.7 to 3.6%, likely mean that the RBA will think it needs to work even harder to get inflation under control. Financial markets are pricing in around a 60% chance that the RBA will raise rates again next month, with Bloomberg data showing that a rate hike by August is a virtual certainty, as are two by the end of the year. If the market is right, that would take Australia's cash rate target to 4.6% from its current level at 4.1%. I guess we'll find out just how resilient the Australian economy is then.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Chalmers says economy is 'resilient' but does that just mean more rate rises until it isn't?
